{"title_page": "Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious building\n| religious_affiliation = [[Jainism]]\n| image          = File:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Main (1).jpg\n| alt            = Vallabh Smarak Jain temple\n| caption        = Vallabh Smarak Jain Mandir Tirth\n| map_type       = \n| map_alt        = Vallabh Smarak Jain temple\n| map_caption    = Location within Delhi\n| map_size       = 200\n| coordinates    = {{coord|28|46|38.7|N|77|08|25.9|E|region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| location       = [[Nangli Poona]], [[GT Karnal road]], [[Delhi]]\n| festivals      = [[Panch Kalyanaka]], [[Samvatsari]], [[Parshva]] - [[Padmavati (Jainism)|Padmawati]] Jagran, Nav dhwajarohan (New flag hosting), Birth & Death Anniversary of Acharya Vallabhsuri & Guru Vallabh Bhakti Samaroh\n| deity          = [[Vasupujya]]\n| established    = 1979 \n| year_completed = 1989\n| creator        = Acharya Indradinsuri \n| governing_body = Shree Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak Shikshan Nidhi\n| temple_quantity = 8\n}}\n\n'''Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak''' or '''Vallabh Smarak Jain Mandir Tirth''' is a [[Jainism|Jain]] temple located in [[Nangli Poona]], [[GT road]], [[Delhi]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe temple's construction was completed in 1989 by the followers of Acharya Vijay [[Vallabhsuri]],{{Sfn|Schnapp|2014|p=431}} to whom the temple is dedicated as a memorial. He is known for establishing several educational institutes in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[Delhi|Haryana]], [[Uttar Pradesh|Uttar Pradesh, Rajasthan, Gujarat & Maharashtra]] including Mahavira Jain Vidhyalaya. He also worked to improve the religious and social life of the people in [[Punjab]], earning him the honorific ''Punjab Kesari''.{{Sfn|Shah|2004|p=55}} The construction of the temple was led by Acharya Samudrasuri to start with and then Acharya Indradinsuri with Mahattaraa Mrigavati being the torch bearer for this project.{{Sfn|Shah|2004|p=44}} At present the activities of this Smarak are carried out under the guidance of Acharya Nityanandsuri - the senior most Acharya and Gachhadhipati of Acharya Vallabh Suri Samuday. \n\nThe temple is managed by Shree Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak Shikshan Nidhi.{{Sfn|Titze|1998|p=136}}\n\n== Architecture ==\n\nThe main hall of the temple is considered a brilliant example of the structural design as per ancient Jain Sthapatya Kala (Main Sompura: Amrutbhai Mulshankar Trivedi). It is built in dome-shaped internally with an external design having stepped roof.{{Sfn|Weiler|Gutschow|2016|p=118-119}} The temple belongs to [[\u015ahv\u0113t\u0101mbara]] sect of [[Jainism]]. The temple itself consists of ancient idols along with the manuscripts, images, sculptures dating back to the [[Medieval India|medieval period]]. The mulnayak of the temple is 12th Tirthanker '''Shree Vasupujya Swami''' placed along with Tirthanker Shree Munisuvrat Swami, Shree Rishabdev & Shree Parshwnath in a typical Chaumukha formation. Many an ancient murals and artifacts  are displayed in the basement Museum. Guru Mandir on the ground floor has a stunning sculpted image of '''Acharya Vallabh Suri''' and His charan paduka. Besides in the circular hall, of 64 feet wide and 84 feet height, are 10 panels of exquisite three dimensional stone work depicting the illustrious life and ideals of Acharya Vallabhsuri.   These images are sourced mainly from [[Gujarat]], [[Rajasthan]] and [[Maharashtra]]. The temple also houses belongings of [[Acharya Vallabh Suri]], including Acharya's clothes, utensils, denture, and inkwell, showcased alongside Jain images and panels.{{Sfn|Schnapp|2014|pp=431-432}} There is a wonderful photo exhibition of Acharya Vallabh Suri in a room just outside the Guru Mandir.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Main Idol.jpg|Mulnayak idol\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Mural.jpg|Murals on wall\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Padmavati idol.jpg|Padmavati Idol\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Padmavati temple (2).jpg|Padmavati temple inside the temple complex\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Main vedi.jpg|Main vedi\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Janma Kalyank.jpg|Janma Kalyanak depiction on wall\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [[Jainism in Delhi]]\n* [[Lal Mandir]]\n* [[D\u0101d\u0101bad\u012b]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Citation ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Source ===\n* {{Citation | last1=Weiler | first1=Katharina | last2=Gutschow | first2=Niels | title=Authenticity in Architectural Heritage Conservation: Discourses, Opinions, Experiences in Europe, South and East Asia | publisher=[[Springer Publishing|Springer]] | date=2016 | url={{Google books|YhOfDAAAQBAJ|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | isbn=9783319305233 }} \n* {{Citation | last=Schnapp | first1=Alain | title=World Antiquarianism: Comparative Perspectives | publisher=Getty Publications | date=2014 | url={{Google books|w0skBAAAQBAJ|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | isbn=9781606061480 }} \n* {{citation | last=Shah | first=Natubhai | title=Jainism: The World of Conquerors | url={{Google books|qLNQKGcDIhsC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | volume=1 | date=2004 | origyear=First published in 1998 | publisher=[[Motilal Banarsidass]] | isbn=978-81-208-1938-2 }}\n* {{Citation | last=Titze | first=Kurt | title=Jainism: A Pictorial Guide to the Religion of Non-Violence | publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publication | date=1998 | url={{Google books|loQkEIf8z5wC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | isbn=9788120815346 }}\n\n{{Jain temples}}\n{{Jainism topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:20th-century Jain temples]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious building\n| religious_affiliation = [[Jainism]]\n| image          = File:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Main (1).jpg\n| alt            = Vallabh Smarak Jain temple\n| caption        = Vallabh Smarak Jain Mandir Tirth\n| map_type       = \n| map_alt        = Vallabh Smarak Jain temple\n| map_caption    = Location within Delhi\n| map_size       = 200\n| coordinates    = {{coord|28|46|38.7|N|77|08|25.9|E|region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| location       = [[Nangli Poona]], [[GT Karnal road]], [[Delhi]]\n| festivals      = [[Panch Kalyanaka]], [[Samvatsari]], [[Parshva]] - [[Padmavati (Jainism)|Padmawati]] Jagran, Nav dhwajarohan (New flag hosting), Birth & Death Anniversary of Acharya Vallabhsuri & Guru Vallabh Bhakti Samaroh\n| deity          = [[Vasupujya]]\n| established    = 1979 \n| year_completed = 1989\n| creator        = Acharya Indradinsuri \n| governing_body = Shree Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak Shikshan Nidhi\n| temple_quantity = 8\n}}\n\n'''Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak''' or '''Vallabh Smarak Jain Mandir Tirth''' is a [[Jainism|Jain]] temple located in [[Nangli Poona]], [[GT road]], [[Delhi]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe temple's construction was completed in 1989 by the followers of Acharya Vijay [[Vallabhsuri]],{{Sfn|Schnapp|2014|p=431}} to whom the temple is dedicated as a memorial. He is known for establishing several educational institutes in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[Delhi|Haryana]], [[Uttar Pradesh|Uttar Pradesh, Rajasthan, Gujarat & Maharashtra]] including Mahavira Jain Vidhyalaya. He also worked to improve the religious and social life of the people in [[Punjab]], earning him the honorific ''Punjab Kesari''.{{Sfn|Shah|2004|p=55}} The construction of the temple was led by Acharya Samudrasuri to start with and then Acharya Indradinsuri with Mahattaraa Mrigavati being the torch bearer for this project.{{Sfn|Shah|2004|p=44}} At present the activities of this Smarak are carried out in the guidance of Acharya Nityanandsuri\n\nThe temple is managed by Shree Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak Shikshan Nidhi.{{Sfn|Titze|1998|p=136}}\n\n== Architecture ==\n\nThe main hall of the temple is considered a brilliant example of the structural design as per ancient Jain Sthapatya Kala (Main Sompura: Amrutbhai Mulshankar Trivedi). It is built in dome-shaped internally with an external design having stepped roof.{{Sfn|Weiler|Gutschow|2016|p=118-119}} The temple belongs to [[\u015ahv\u0113t\u0101mbara]] sect of [[Jainism]]. The temple itself consists of ancient idols along with the manuscripts, images, sculptures dating back to the [[Medieval India|medieval period]]. The mulnayak of the temple is 12th Tirthanker '''Shree Vasupujya Swami''' placed along with Tirthanker Shree Munisuvrat Swami, Shree Rishabdev & Shree Parshwnath in a typical Chaumukha formation. Many an ancient murals and artifacts  are displayed in the basement Museum. Guru Mandir on the ground floor has a stunning sculpted image of '''Acharya Vallabh Suri''' and His charan paduka. Besides in the circular hall, of 64 feet wide and 84 feet height, are 10 panels of exquisite three dimensional stone work depicting the illustrious life and ideals of Acharya Vallabhsuri.   These images are sourced mainly from [[Gujarat]], [[Rajasthan]] and [[Maharashtra]]. The temple also houses belongings of [[Acharya Vallabh Suri]], including Acharya's clothes, utensils, denture, and inkwell, showcased alongside Jain images and panels.{{Sfn|Schnapp|2014|pp=431-432}} There is a wonderful photo exhibition of Acharya Vallabh Suri in a room just outside the Guru Mandir.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Main Idol.jpg|Mulnayak idol\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Mural.jpg|Murals on wall\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Padmavati idol.jpg|Padmavati Idol\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Padmavati temple (2).jpg|Padmavati temple inside the temple complex\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Main vedi.jpg|Main vedi\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Janma Kalyank.jpg|Janma Kalyanak depiction on wall\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [[Jainism in Delhi]]\n* [[Lal Mandir]]\n* [[D\u0101d\u0101bad\u012b]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Citation ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Source ===\n* {{Citation | last1=Weiler | first1=Katharina | last2=Gutschow | first2=Niels | title=Authenticity in Architectural Heritage Conservation: Discourses, Opinions, Experiences in Europe, South and East Asia | publisher=[[Springer Publishing|Springer]] | date=2016 | url={{Google books|YhOfDAAAQBAJ|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | isbn=9783319305233 }} \n* {{Citation | last=Schnapp | first1=Alain | title=World Antiquarianism: Comparative Perspectives | publisher=Getty Publications | date=2014 | url={{Google books|w0skBAAAQBAJ|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | isbn=9781606061480 }} \n* {{citation | last=Shah | first=Natubhai | title=Jainism: The World of Conquerors | url={{Google books|qLNQKGcDIhsC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | volume=1 | date=2004 | origyear=First published in 1998 | publisher=[[Motilal Banarsidass]] | isbn=978-81-208-1938-2 }}\n* {{Citation | last=Titze | first=Kurt | title=Jainism: A Pictorial Guide to the Religion of Non-Violence | publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publication | date=1998 | url={{Google books|loQkEIf8z5wC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | isbn=9788120815346 }}\n\n{{Jain temples}}\n{{Jainism topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:20th-century Jain temples]]\n", "name_user": "GS AV Mahasangh", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shri_Atma_Vallabh_Jain_Smarak"}
{"title_page": "Moonlight (XXXTentacion song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = back\n\n\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[XXXTentacion]]\n| album      = [[? (XXXTentacion album)|?]]\n| released   = August 14, 2018\n\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = \n| length     = 2:15\n| label      = {{hlist|Bad Vibes Forever|[[Caroline Distribution|Caroline]]}}\n| writer     = [[XXXTentacion]]\n| producer   = [[XXXTentacion]]\n| chronology = [[XXXTentacion]]\n| prev_title = Ghostbusters\n| prev_year  = 2018\n| next_title = [[Falling Down (Lil Peep and XXXTentacion song)|Falling Down]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|GX8Hg6kWQYI|\"Moonlight\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Moonlight'''\" is a song written and performed by American rapper [[XXXTentacion]] from his second studio album ''[[? (XXXTentacion album)|?]]''. The song was posthumously sent to [[rhythmic contemporary|rhythmic radio]] as the album's third single on August 14, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2018/08/22/travis-scotts-sicko-mode-ranks-rhythmic-radios-added-song/|title=Travis Scott\u2019s \"SICKO MODE\" Ranks As Rhythmic Radio\u2019s Most Added Song|date=August 22, 2018|work=Headline Planet|accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8477612/xxxtentacion-moonlight-video|title=Watch XXXTentacion Calmly Collect His Thoughts in 'Moonlight' Video|date=October 1, 2018|work=Billboard|accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref> The song reached many chart positions globally, including a number 13 peak on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] as well as a platinum certification following his death. It's therefore tied with \"[[Falling Down (Lil Peep and XXXTentacion song)|Falling Down]]\" (with [[Lil Peep]]) as his third-highest charting song in the United States, with both songs falling behind \"[[Sad!]]\" and \"[[Don't Cry (Lil Wayne song)|Don't Cry]]\" (with [[Lil Wayne]]).\n\n==Music video==\nThe official music video for \"Moonlight\" was released on the early night of October 1, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/video/2018/10/xxxtentacion-moonlight-video/|title=XXXTentacion \"Moonlight\" Video: Watch The Late Rapper Wander Through The Night|date=October 1, 2018|work=XXL|accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> The video was written and creative directed by Onfroy himself, and was also directed by JMP. The video features Onfroy and a large group of people at a get-together taking place in the woods after dark, lit by the light of a full moon. Onfroy is seen sitting by himself listening to headphones and observing the party, as well as walking through the crowd of people who are all dressed in black attire. He laughs as he watches people dance, and also exchanges stares with a mysterious curly-haired girl who is shown several times during the video (based on her appearance she has been theorized to represent Geneva Ayala, Onfroy's ex-girlfriend). Having been released after the rapper's passing, the video ends with the phrases \"ENERGY NEVER DIES\", \"HE IS AMONGST US\" and \"LONG LIVE JAH\" in tribute to Onfroy. A similar phrase, \"LONG LIVE PRINCE X\", was also featured at the end of his \"SAD!\" music video.\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n* [[XXXTentacion]] \u2013 vocals, songwriting, composition\n* John Cunningham \u2013 songwriting, composition, production, mixing\n* Robert Soukiasyan \u2013 mixing, recording, studio personnel\n* Dave Kutch \u2013 mastering, studio personnel\n* Kevin Peterson \u2013 mastering assistant\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2018)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br /> position\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|22|artist=XXXTentacion|song=Moonlight|rowheader=true|accessdate=