{"title_page": "1994 FIBA World Championship", "text_new": "{{short description|1994 edition of the FIBA World Championship}}\n{{about|1994 FIBA World Championship for Men|the equivalent games for women players|1994 FIBA World Championship for Women}}\n{{Infobox international basketball competition\n| tourney_name   = FIBA World Championship\n| year           = 1994\n| other_titles   = Championnat du monde de basket-ball masculin 1994\n| image          = FIBA 1994 Logo.png\n| size           = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| city           = \n| country        =Canada\n| dates          = August 4 \u2013 August 14\n| num_teams      = 16\n| federations  = 200\n| venues        = 3\n| cities        = 2\n| champion      = United States\n| count         = 3\n| second        = Russia\n| third         = Croatia\n| fourth        = Greece\n| games         = \n| attendance    = \n| mvp           = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Shaquille O'Neal]]\n| top_scorer    =  {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Andrew Gaze]] <br>(23.9 [[points per game]])\n| prevseason    = [[1990 FIBA World Championship|1990]]\n| nextseason    = [[1998 FIBA World Championship|1998]]\n| updated       =\n}}\nThe '''1994 FIBA World Championship''' was the 12th [[FIBA World Championship]], the international [[basketball]] world championship for men's teams. The tournament was hosted by Canada from August 4 to August 14, 1994. The tournament was held at [[Rogers Centre|SkyDome]]<ref>[[The New York Times]], [https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/15/sports/basketball-dream-team-ends-its-sequel-predictably.html  BASKETBALL; Dream Team Ends Its Sequel Predictably]</ref> and [[Maple Leaf Gardens]] in [[Toronto]]<ref name=\"nytimes\">''The New York Times'', [https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/06/sports/sports-of-the-times-toronto-dream-team-the-world.html Sports of The Times; Toronto, Dream Team, The World]</ref> as well as at [[Copps Coliseum]] in [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]].<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> The hosting duties were originally awarded to [[Belgrade]], [[Yugoslavia]], but after [[United Nations]] [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 757|limited participation in sporting events in Yugoslavia]], Toronto stepped in as a replacement option in 1992.\n\nThe 1994 FIBA World Championship was the first time that the FIBA World Championship (now called [[FIBA Basketball World Cup]]) allowed current American NBA players that had already played in an official NBA regular season game to participate. Prior to that only professionals from other leagues were allowed to compete, since players from other leagues were still considered amateurs.<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/why-can-pros-complete-in-international-events.aspx</ref>\n\nThe tournament was won by the United States's [[United States men's national basketball team#1994 World Championship Team \u2013 Dream Team II|''Dream Team II'']], who beat [[Russia national basketball team|Russia]] 137\u201391 in the Final. The United States finished with a perfect 8\u20130 record (8 wins and 0 losses). The bronze medal was won by [[Croatia men's national basketball team|Croatia]] who beat [[Greece national basketball team|Greece]] 78\u201360 in the bronze-medal game.\n\n==Venues==\nThree stadia were used during the tournament:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=2|[[Toronto]]\n! [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]\n|-\n| [[Rogers Centre|SkyDome]]\n| [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n| [[Copps Coliseum]]\n|-\n| Capacity: '''28,708'''\n| Capacity: '''16,538'''\n| Capacity: '''18,436'''\n|-\n| [[Image:RogersCentre Toronto Sept1-05.jpg|150px]]\n| [[Image:Maple Leaf Gardens, east side.JPG|150px]]\n| [[Image:CoppsColiseumYorkBoulevard.JPG|150px]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|{{Location map+ |Canada Southern Ontario|width=450 |float=center |caption= |places=\n{{Location map~ |Canada Southern Ontario|lat=43.641389 |long=-79.389167 |label=[[Rogers Centre|SkyDome]] |position=top |marksize=8 }}\n{{Location map~ |Canada Southern Ontario|lat=43.662222 |long=-79.380278 |label=[[Maple Leaf Gardens]] |position=right |marksize=8}}\n{{Location map~ |Canada Southern Ontario|lat=43.25916 |long=-79.8725 |label=[[Copps Coliseum]] |position=bottom|marksize=8}}\n}}\n|}\n\n==Competing nations==\nThe following national teams competed:\n\n{{Col begin}}\n{{Col-4}}\n;[[FIBA Africa Championship 1993|FIBA Africa]] (2)\n*{{Bk|ANG}}\n*{{Bk|EGY}}\n;[[1993 ABC Championship|FIBA Asia]] (2)\n*{{Bk|CHN}}\n*{{Bk|KOR}} *\n{{Col-4}}\n;[[1993 Tournament of the Americas|FIBA Americas]] (4+2)\n*{{Bk|ARG}}\n*{{Bk|BRA}}\n*{{Bk|CAN}} (Host Nation)\n*{{Bk|CUB}}\n*{{Bk|PUR|1952}}\n*{{Bk|USA}} (Olympic Champions)\n;[[1993 FIBA Oceania Championship|FIBA Oceania]] (1)\n*{{Bk|AUS}}\n{{Col-4}}\n;[[EuroBasket 1993|FIBA Europe]] (5)\n*{{Bk|CRO}}\n*{{Bk|GER}}\n*{{Bk|GRE}}\n*{{Bk|RUS}}\n*{{Bk|ESP}}\n{{Col-4}}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> {{Bk|PRK}} withdrew from the tournament, {{Bk|KOR}} replaced them.\n\n==Preliminary round==\n{| class=\"infobox bordered\"\n|-\n|width=10px bgcolor=\"#ccffcc\"| ||Qualified for the second round groups I and II\n|-\n|width=10px bgcolor=\"#ffffcc\"| ||Qualified for the second round groups III and IV\n|}\nThe top two teams from each group remain in medal contention.\n\n===Group A===\n{{Bs cl2 header navbar}}\n{{Bs cl2 team|t={{Bk|USA}} |w=3 |l=0 |pf=352 |pa=259 |bc=#ccffcc}}\n{{Bs cl2 team|t={{Bk|CHN}} |w=2 |l=1 |pf=259 |pa=301 |bc=#ccffcc}}\n{{Bs cl2 team|t={{Bk|ESP}} |w=1 |l=2 |pf=249 |pa=260 |bc=#ffffcc}}\n{{Bs cl2 team|t={{Bk|BRA}} |w=0 |l=3 |pf=242 |pa=275 |bc=#ffffcc}}\n|}\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=4 August |place=[[Copps Coliseum]], [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] |overtime=OT\n|teamA='''{{bk-rt|CHN}} '''|scoreA='''97'''\n|teamB={{bk|BRA}} |scoreB=93\n}}\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=4 August |place=[[Copps Coliseum]], [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]\n|teamA='''{{bk-rt|USA}}''' |scoreA='''115'''\n|teamB={{bk|ESP}} |scoreB=100\n}}\n{{basketballbox|date=5 August |place=[[Copps Coliseum]], [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]\